  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 5.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "But as one was felling a beam",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " a tree, to make it into a beam - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "the axe-head",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; literally, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "the iron",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". We see from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 19:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " that the Hebrews made their axe-heads of iron as early as the time of Moses. They probably learnt to smelt and work iron in Egypt. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Fell into the water.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The tree must have been one that grew close to the river's edge. As the man hewed away at the stem a little above the root, the axe-head flew from the haft, into which it was insecurely fitted, and fell into the water. The slipping of an axe-head was a very common occurrence (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 19:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and ordinarily was of little consequence, since it was easily restored to its place. But now the head had disappeared. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And he cried, and said, Alas, master!",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - rather, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Alas",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "my master",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "! or, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Alas",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "my lord",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "! - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "for it was borrowed",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; rather, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "and it was a borrowed one",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The words are part of the man's address to Elisha. He means to say, \"It is no common misfortune; it is not as if it had been my own axe. I had borrowed it, and now what shall I say to the owner?\" There is no direct request for help, but the tone of the complaint constitutes a sort of silent appeal. 2 Kings 6:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "In the felling of the beams, the iron, i.e., the axe, of one of the pupils of the prophets fell into the water, at which he exclaimed with lamentation: \"Alas, my lord (i.e., Elisha), and it was begged!\" The sorrowful exclamation implied a petition for help. ואת־הבּרזל: \"and as for the iron, it fell into the water;\" so that even here את does not stand before the nominative, but serves to place the noun in subjection to the clause (cf. Ewald, 277, a.). שׁאוּל does not mean borrowed, but begged. The meaning to borrow is attributed to שׁאל from a misinterpretation of particular passages (see the Comm. on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 3:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The prophets' pupil had begged the axe, because from his poverty he was unable to buy one, and hence the loss was so painful to him. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]